 then is given XP that coincides with the difficulty of the task at hand.  Should he fail, he could attempt again on that lock, but should he be successful, there is no XP reward for that lock.  This could be done for not just thief skills, but also turning undead, knowledge skills, or other skills that are not persistent.<br><br>I'm aware that a DM can reward characters XP as they deem appropriate, but this would allow for the DM to do other tasks, rather than checking each character to see if they need to be given XP for something that is a part of their profession.  Also, it gets away from the classic D&amp;D idea that XP is only given out for combat.  I detest that kind of thinking, and feels it only pushes the game more towards being hack &amp; slash, versus expanding the dimensions of what the game is about.<br><br><br>Larlana <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000028><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub77.ezboard.com/ularlanalavode.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Larlana Lavode</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 209<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(7/19/02 4:31:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub77.ezboard.com/ftallonzektimes4735frm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=109.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Experience Distribution (GM help, please)</span><hr size=1> Just found out that there IS a major bug with experience, giving out too much experience by somehow multiplying the amount by the character's level, and then either doubling or tripling that amount (or something like this), because of having either a familiar, henchman, and/or summoned help.  And people wonder why they are breezing through the solo player game so fast.<br><br>Here's a link to the thread, and apparently BioWare hasn't made mention of this bug, but at the end, some people have mentioned about possible fixes for it.<br><br><!--EZ